<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,1625,2010]" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,499,1769,1794]" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[507,734,1769,1794]" class="Reptilia" family="Teiidae" genus="Kentropyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="415" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pelviceps">
<emphasis box="[507,734,1769,1794]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">Kentropyx pelviceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to western Amazonia, with its eastern distribution restricted by the 
<collectingRegion box="[343,484,1805,1830]" country="Uruguay" name="Rio Negro" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">Negro River</collectingRegion>
north of the Amazon, and by the Madeira River basin (both sides in the upper and middle portions, west side in the lower portion), occurring in 
<collectingCountry box="[834,905,1841,1866]" name="Brazil" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[916,1029,1841,1866]" name="Colombia" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1039,1134,1841,1866]" name="Ecuador" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1145,1199,1842,1865]" name="Peru" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">Peru</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[1257,1340,1841,1866]" name="Bolivia" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[1354,1422,1841,1866]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1545,1567]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,277,1505]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1436,267,1523]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 9. Distribution of examined material of Kentropyx calcarata, K. pelviceps, and Salvator merianae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/197986/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry box="[182,250,1877,1902]" name="Brazil" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">Brazil</collectingCountry>
it is known from the states of 
<collectingRegion box="[597,718,1878,1902]" country="Peru" name="Amazonas" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">Amazonas</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[731,788,1878,1902]" country="Brazil" name="Acre" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">Acre</collectingRegion>
, and 
<collectingRegion box="[848,961,1877,1902]" country="Brazil" name="Rondonia" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">Rondônia</collectingRegion>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[972,1199,1877,1902]" class="Reptilia" family="Teiidae" genus="Kentropyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="415" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pelviceps">
<emphasis box="[972,1199,1877,1902]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">Kentropyx pelviceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is semi-arboreal and diurnal, inhabits primary and secondary terra firme and 
<taxonomicName box="[787,860,1914,1937]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Varzea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="426" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">varzea</taxonomicName>
forests, where it is found mainly on the ground or low on trunks and branches of fallen trees (occasionally up to 3.5 meters high), most often in and around sunny spots (
<bibRefCitation author="Fitch" box="[225,353,1985,2010]" pageId="14" pageNumber="415" refString="Fitch, H. S. (1968) Temperature and behavior of some Equatorial lizards. Herpetologica, 24, 35 - 38." type="journal article" year="1968">Fitch 1968</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Dixon" box="[367,605,1985,2010]" pageId="14" pageNumber="415" refString="Dixon, J. R. &amp; Soini, P. (1975) The reptiles of the upper Amazon Basin, Iquitos region, Peru. Part 1. Lizards and Amphisbaenians. Milwaukee Public Museum, Contributions in Biology and Geology, 4, 1 - 58." type="journal article" year="1975">Dixon &amp; Soini 1975</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Duellman" box="[620,798,1985,2010]" pageId="14" pageNumber="415" refString="Duellman, W. E. (1978) The biology of an Equatorial Herpetofauna in Amazonian Ecuador. Miscellaneous Publications, Museum of Natural History of University of Kansas, 65, 1 - 352." type="journal article" year="1978">Duellman 1978</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Gallagher" box="[813,1102,1985,2010]" pageId="14" pageNumber="415" refString="Gallagher, D. S. Jr. &amp; Dixon, J. R. (1992) Taxonomic revision of the South American lizard genus Kentropyx Spix (Sauria: Teiidae). Bollettino del Museo Regionale di Scienze Naturali, Torino, 10, 125 - 171." type="journal article" year="1992">Gallagher &amp; Dixon 1992</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Avila-Pires" box="[1116,1312,1985,2010]" pageId="14" pageNumber="415" refString="Avila-Pires, T. C. S. (1995) Lizards of Brazilian Amazonia (Reptilia: Squamata). Zoologische Verhandelingen, 299, 1 - 706." type="journal article" year="1995">Ávila-Pires 1995</bibRefCitation>
; Vitt 
<emphasis box="[1377,1436,1985,2010]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">et al.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
